description: MathML, or the Mathematical Markup Language, describes mathematical notation, such as expressions and formulas. Also known as MathML Core.
description_html: MathML, or the Mathematical Markup Language, describes mathematical notation, such as expressions and formulas. Also known as MathML Core.
name: MathML

compat.description: Nonzero unitless values (e.g. 5 to mean 500% the default thickness)

chrome.notes: Removed in Chrome 25 because code was not yet production ready.

notes: The only allowed value in MathML Core is 'normal'. Firefox enables a number of other deprecated values from the MathML 3 specification (see bug 1845461).

firefox.notes: Support for negative values has been implemented in Firefox 23.

firefox_android.notes: Support for negative values has been implemented in Firefox for Android 23.

notes: In Firefox 29, accepted attributes have been restricted to those actually used in practice: id, class, style, href, mathcolor, mathbackground, scriptlevel, displaystyle, scriptsizemultiplier, scriptminsize, dir, mathsize, mathvariant, fontfamily, fontweight, fontstyle, fontsize, color, background.
In Firefox 103, attributes scriptsizemultiplier and scriptminsize have been removed.

In Firefox for Android 29, accepted attributes have been restricted to those actually used in practice: id, class, style, href, mathcolor, mathbackground, scriptlevel, displaystyle, scriptsizemultiplier, scriptminsize, dir, mathsize, mathvariant, fontfamily, fontweight, fontstyle, fontsize, color, background.
In Firefox for Android 103, attributes scriptsizemultiplier and scriptminsize have been removed.

firefox.notes: Prior to Firefox 70, the attribute was only accepted on a few elements, as specified in MathML 3.

firefox_android.notes: Prior to Firefox for Android 79, the attribute was only accepted on a few elements, as specified in MathML 3.

firefox.notes: Prior to Firefox 83, the attribute was only accepted on a few elements, as specified in MathML 3, and was not implemented via math-style.

firefox_android.notes: Prior to Firefox for Android 83, the attribute was only accepted on a few elements, as specified in MathML 3, and was not implemented via math-style.

safari.notes: Since Safari 14.1, this attribute is implemented via math-style.

safari_ios.notes: Since Safari on iOS 14.1, this attribute is implemented via math-style.

webview_ios.notes: Since WebView on iOS 14.1, this attribute is implemented via math-style.
